# Watch a video

Prepare a video for analysis using the `watch.py` script that ships with this rule. Captions come from yt-dlp (auto-subs); frames come from ffmpeg. No third-party transcription service.

## When to trigger

The user shares a video URL or local video file path and asks anything about its contents — what was said, what was shown, who appears, what happens at a timestamp, etc.

## How to run

Find the script at `~/.claude/skills/watch/scripts/watch.py` (or wherever the user installed `claude-watch-yt`).

```bash
python3 ~/.claude/skills/watch/scripts/watch.py "<source>" [--mode {fast,balanced,accurate}] [--start TIME] [--end TIME]
```

The script auto-installs ffmpeg and yt-dlp on first run.

## Modes (token vs accuracy)

- `fast` — 15 frames @ 320px. Captions carry the content. ~10-20k image tokens.
- `balanced` (default) — 25 frames @ 384px. Most general questions. ~25-60k.
- `accurate` — 60 frames @ 512px. Precise visual details (slides, code, dense action). ~80-200k.

Pick the lowest mode that answers the question. Default to `balanced` when unsure.

## Workflow

1. Run the script. It prints a markdown summary: metadata, transcript (if captions available), and a list of frame paths with timestamps.
2. Read the transcript first — it usually answers the question alone.
3. Only read frames that are necessary. Use Read on specific frame paths from the index. Don't load every frame.
4. Cite timestamps in your answer (e.g., "At [02:14], …").
5. When done, suggest the user delete the work directory shown in the output.

## Constraints

- For videos over 15 minutes, narrow with `--start`/`--end` first.
- Bump `--resolution` to 768+ only when the user needs to read tiny on-screen text.
- If captions are unavailable, the script switches to vision-only mode automatically (denser frames). Tell the user transcript wasn't available and you're going off visuals alone.
